76561198007895634,Recommended,396090,19722249,"Posted: 15 December, 2015",all,penargyl,"Rogue State is a government management role playing game set after an Arab Spring type event.  Each year is divided into several turns.  Given the topical nature of the game and limited but repayable scenario I recommend it for those who want to experience a fairly standard government game with unique flavor.  The graphics and sound are functional and some of the touches, like having the U.S. ambassador answer the phone and meet you, are cute touches but one wonders if the time would have been better spent elsewhere.Rogue State occupies an incredible is the sense of place and time.  The setup is that you’re managing a newly formed country after an Arab Spring style uprising and must appoint your more popular younger brother to the cabinet.  You must balance the wants of multiple factions (Capitalists, Liberals, the religious community, etc.), security concerns, economic growth, and foreign policy with three neighbors.  Overlooking all of this is the United States.  The Role of the U.S. is similar to the cold war powers in the Tropico franchise.  While able to be used as a boon too much negativity could lead to an unacceptable outcome.To a gamer that has managed elf kingdoms, star empires, defeated the Allies and communist scum in WWII what Rogue State provides is a truly unique sense of place and time.  That the events are closely modelled on recent events in our world are truly interesting and show a great care by the creators.Rogue State is as much an “art” indie game like Gone Home, The Novelist, or Papers Please.  By playing on a gamer’s sense of min/maxing it creates interesting choices between doing the “Right” thing, roleplaying a certain style of government, and winning the game.  Enough options exist to survive several playthroughs even with a fairly linear story that you will lose at least once.In many ways this game feels more suited towards being an IPad or Facebook game.  The turn based structure gives incremental returns and at least one choice per turn.  The game typically is spent making a choice, waiting for the impacts to be felt, and managing a request from a faction or foreign power.  Balancing limited resources creates several “Ah-ha” moments during the first few playthroughs but a limited A.I. ends up making other subsequent games more about experiencing different story branches.I would recommend a purchase and play of Rouge State given the setting and interesting flavor."
76561198044913452,Recommended,396090,19278625,"Posted: 25 November, 2015",all,UserNamesAre4Plebs,"After purchasing this game and playing it for a few hours I have come to the conclusion that it was worth buying.The developers of this game truly have put in a lot of work towards creating an expereince which incorporates a variety of factors that must be fulfilled in order for one to be succesful, thus creating an equally interesting and challenging experience for the player.While the graphics are certainly up to a satisfactory standard the gameplay itself gets a little stale after a while - not necessarily because there aren't enough events occuring throughout the game but rather because of its very nature.There is only that much that the developers can do with this particular type of Indie-game, but what bothers me at times is the limited speed of the characters movement, the events occuring in response to such, and the repetitve events in response to my actions.To sum it up:Pros;- Detail-rich gameworld- Interesting characters, each with their own unique personality- A pleasing limit of resources (e.g. money) that create scenarios in which it is crucial to make a decisive choice- The humour of the game itself (Chickenistan)- Blend of politics, economics, and military strategyCons;- Slow movement of the characters, thus prolonging the game unnecessarily- Repetitive personalities despite the fact that the characters are frequently with every new game started.- Trade with neighbouring states does not significantly impact the game itself, thus failing to create a wholesome economic simulation.So at the end of the day this game is totaly worth buying.  If you are an Indie fan then I would definetely recommend this to you, though keep in mind that I personally do not feel as if it is worth the current 12.99 EUR they are charging for it - I bought it when it was on a 50% sale - in my opinion that is more apropriate of a price.Please continue on making similar games, I will definetely buy them and can only re-iterate that this game is equally interesting and challenging."
